               <dir-list>
                    <dir-entry id="IO-UN.PB.0012" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="DIR-ENTRYREF">
                         <dir-entry-name>Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General for West Africa and the Sahel, Head of Office</dir-entry-name>
                         <person-group>
                              <person>
                                   <person-name>
                                        <forename>Léonardo</forename>
                                        <surname>Santos Simão</surname>
                                   </person-name>
                                   <person-note>Mozambique</person-note>
                              </person>
                         </person-group>
                    </dir-entry>
               </dir-list>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Establishment and Mandate</heading>
                    <p>
          UNOWAS was established in January 2016 through a merger of the former UN Office for West Africa (UNOWA, established in 2002) and the Office of the Special Envoy for the Sahel, to provide preventive diplomacy, good offices, and political mediation and facilitation efforts in the combined region. UNOWAS is also mandated to support the implementation of the October 2002 ruling of the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-UN.527">International Court of Justice</xr>
           relating to land and maritime boundaries between Cameroon and Nigeria; the Cameroon-Nigeria Mixed Commission, chaired by the Special Representative of the Secretary-General (SRSG) meets regularly in this respect.
        </p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Activities</heading>
                    <p>UNOWAS supports regional institutions and member states to enhance their capacities to promote good governance, respect for the rule of law, human rights and the mainstreaming of gender in conflict prevention. It also assists the consolidation of democratic governance, stability and development in post-crisis countries in the region, and provides support to strategies aimed at resolving cross-cutting security threats—such as violent extremism, terrorism, transnational organized crime, and maritime piracy.</p>
                    <p usage="edio ass">
          UNOWAS co-operates closely on security matters with, 
          <i>inter alia,</i>
           the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="AU.IO">African Union</xr>
           (AU), the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="ECOWAS.IO">Economic Community of West African States</xr>
           (ECOWAS), the Lake Chad Basin Commission (LCBC), the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="WB0231XB.IO.TXT.90">Mano River Union</xr>
           (comprising Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone), and the Gulf of Guinea Commission. A trilateral partnership is pursued between UNOWAS, the European Union and 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="ECOWAS.IO">ECOWAS</xr>
          . UNOWAS chairs biannual high-level meetings of the heads of UN missions in West Africa. The 38th such meeting, convened in September 2023, in Dakar, Senegal, stated concern over recent multiple unconstitutional changes of governments in the region, emphasizing the need promptly to restore constitutional order. A UNOWAS-UN Office for Central Africa co-ordination meeting is held annually. In March 2022 the Deputy SRSG chaired the inaugural annual Women's Forum for Peace and Security in West Africa and the Sahel, organized under UNOWAS-ECOWAS auspices in Nouakchott, Mauritania.
        </p>
                    <!--G5 Sahel-->
                    <p>UNOWAS supports the implementation of the Code of Conduct concerning the Prevention and Repression of Piracy, Armed Robbery against Ships, and Illegal Maritime Activities in West and Central Africa, which was opened for signature at a regional summit held in Yaoundé, Cameroon, in June 2013 (and is thus referred to as the Yaoundé Code of Conduct).</p>
                    <p>Addressing the root causes of the presence of Boko Haram in the Lake Chad Basin was a focus of UN Security Council Resolution 2347, adopted in March 2017. UNOWAS supported the development of the Regional Stabilization, Recovery and Resilience Strategy for Areas Affected by Boko Haram in the Lake Chad Basin, which was adopted in August 2018 by an AU-LCBC ministerial conference. In August 2020 UNOWAS and UNOCA were designated as co-leaders of the governance cluster of the regional task force guiding the implementation of the Strategy. In January 2024 the UN Secretary-General reported that the scale of Islamic State violence was greater in West Africa and the Sahel than in other parts of Africa, with Islamic State West Africa Province (ISWAP) remaining the most active affiliate in the region. However, an increase in military offensives by regional and national forces, as well as ISWAP-Boko Haram clashes were reported to have contributed to an overall decline in terrorist attacks. Both ISWAP and Boko Haram were reported to be struggling to raise sufficient funds to pay their recruits and thus unable to attract foreign fighters.</p>
                    <p>UNOWAS is the implementing agency of the UN Integrated Strategy for the Sahel (UNISS—endorsed in June 2013 by the UN Security Council), which aims to enhance governance, resilience and security in that sub-region, where, from 2016, conflict that had originated in 2012 in Mali spilled over into Burkina Faso and Niger. The SRSG chairs its steering committee. In mid-2022 a regional platform for regional youth was initiated under UNISS.</p>
                    <p>UNOWAS has supported the development of the Accra Initiative, which focuses on strengthening co-operation on security issues in West Africa and the Sahel. In March 2023 UNOWAS helped to organize a Grand Rendez-vous for the Prevention of Violent Extremism in West and Central Africa, in Dakar, which addressed the regional implementation of the UN Action Plan to Prevent Violent Extremism.</p>
                    <!--G5 Sahel-->
                    <p>
          In July 2023 the UN Secretary-General reported, alongside a worsening regional humanitarian situation (given, 
          <i>inter alia</i>
          , elevated prices for food and other essential commodities), a continuing deterioration in the security situation in the Sahel region—notably in Burkina Faso and Mali, where the al-Qa`ida-affiliated Jama'a Nusrat ul-Islam wa al-Muslimin (JNIM) and Islamic State in the Greater Sahara (ISGS) were competing over access to resources and influence and were persistently attacking civilian and military targets. Meanwhile, the reach of terrorist activities and transnational organized crime was spilling over southwards to coastal West African countries; renewed armed incursions into Benin and Togo were reported. In January 2024 the Secretary-General observed that a localized détente had recently arisen between ISGS and JNIM—freeing both groupings to focus more resources towards other targets.
        </p>
                    <p>In January 2024 the UN Security Council emphasized the role of UNOWAS in working with the UN country team to support the transition authorities in Mali, following the withdrawal of the longstanding UN Multidimensional Integrated Stabilization Mission in Mali (MINUSMA) on 31 December 2023.</p>
                    <p>UNOWAS, ECOWAS and the Mano River Union co-operate in reviewing the implementation of the latter’s Strategy for Cross-Border Security in the Mano River Union. In February 2020 UNOWAS and the Mano River Union adopted a framework of co-operation with a focus on peace and security and on supporting young people and women in the sub-region.</p>
                    <p usage="edio">UNOWAS chairs a regional working group that addresses the prevention and resolution of farmer-herder conflicts in West Africa and the Sahel. In early 2020 UNOWAS published a handbook on related good practices.</p>
                    <p>By March 2024 the Cameroon-Nigeria Mixed Commission had surveyed and determined 2,065 km of the 2,100 km boundary between the two countries.</p>
                    <p usage="ass">In June 2021 UNOWAS, the United Nations Environment Programme and partners inaugurated a UN Regional Working Group to address the environment, climate change, security and development in West Africa.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-block>
     </int-org-entry>
     <int-org-entry id="IO-UN.PB.0004.1" iso="io-un.pb.0004.1" print-style="COLUMN" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-ENTRYREF" usage="ewyb edio mena">
          <int-org-entry-head>
               <int-org-name-group type="MAIN">
                    <org-entry-name>Office of the United Nations Special Coordinator for Lebanon</org-entry-name>
                    <abbr>UNSCOL</abbr>
               </int-org-name-group>
          </int-org-entry-head>
          <int-org-block>
               <address-block>
                    <address type="POSTAL">
                         <verbatim-address>UN House, Riad el-Solh Sq., POB 11, 8577 Beirut, Lebanon</verbatim-address>
                    </address>
                    <email>unscolwebsite@un.org</email>
                    <internet>unscol.unmissions.org</internet>
               </address-block>
               <dir-list>
                    <dir-entry id="IO-UN.PB.0005.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="DIR-ENTRYREF">
                         <dir-entry-name>Special Coordinator for Lebanon</dir-entry-name>
                         <person-group>
                              <person>
                                   <person-name>
                                        <forename>Jeanine</forename>
                                        <surname>Hennis-Plasschaert</surname>
                                   </person-name>
                                   <person-note>Netherlands</person-note>
                              </person>
                         </person-group>
                    </dir-entry>
               </dir-list>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Establishment and Mandate</heading>
                    <p>UNSCOL was established in February 2007. The mission is the focal point for the core group of donor countries supporting Lebanon (through an annually updated Lebanon Crisis Response Plan), and co-ordinates the UN presence within Lebanon. It works closely with the UN peacekeeping mission in Lebanon, UNIFIL. The Special Coordinator is responsible for supervising the implementation of Security Council Resolution 1701, which was adopted in August 2006, and called for a cessation of hostilities in Lebanon. UNSCOL comprises divisions of administration, political, co-ordination, public information, and security. The Special Coordinator works closely with the International Support Group (ISG) for Lebanon, which addresses means of supporting Lebanon in view of the impact on the country’s resources of the crisis in neighbouring Syria. The inaugural meeting was convened in October 2019 of a joint UNSCOL-UN Interim Force in Lebanon strategic forum, with a view to enhancing efficiencies between the two entities.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Activities</heading>
                    <p>In January 2020—following the resignation of the Lebanese Prime Minister, Saad Hariri, in October 2019 (prompted by a wave of national anti-Government protests)—the ISG welcomed the formation of a new Lebanese Government, under the premiership of Hassan Diab. In August 2020 the Special Coordinator expressed solidarity with the victims of the major chemical explosion that had recently devastated the vicinity of the port of Beirut. Widespread demonstrations after the explosion prompted the resignation on 10 August of Prime Minister Diab. Saad Hariri was reappointed as Prime Minister in October; he did not, however, name a new government, and Diab remained in the role of caretaker Prime Minister. UNSCOL subsequently reiterated demands for the prompt formation of an empowered government.</p>
                    <p>In November 2020 the Special Coordinator reported to the UN Security Council that a continuing state of extreme economic crisis in Lebanon, compounded by impacts of the COVID-19 pandemic crisis, was generating deep poverty and food insecurity for increasing numbers of citizens and refugees, in a situation where there was no adequate social protection system. In March 2021, as protests intensified across Lebanon, the ISG, meeting in Beirut, noted the accelerating socioeconomic deterioration, urged restraint, and called for transparent investigations into the Beirut port explosion as well as into the murder (in February) of a prominent political activist, Lokman Mohsen Slim. The inaugural meeting was convened in March of a Consultative Group of the Reform, Recovery and Reconstruction Framework (3RF), comprising representatives of the Lebanese Government and civil society, the UN, EU, World Bank, and international donors. In mid-July Hariri withdrew from the process of forming a new administration; in response, President Michel Aoun convened binding consultations, which led to the appointment of Najib Mikati to the premiership (Mikati was a former incumbent of the role). In August the ISG stated regret over fatalities and injuries caused by the recent explosion of a fuel tanker in northern Lebanon; the incident also aggravated ongoing acute fuel shortages, which were causing disruptions to essential services. The Special Coordinator welcomed the formation of a new administration in September, under Prime Minister Mikati, and reaffirmed the UN’s support for strengthening Lebanese sovereignty, stability and political independence. UNSCOL hosted a digital dialogue in April, with participation by Lebanese youth. The Special Coordinator welcomed the conduct of a general election that was held in May. In October she commended a landmark agreement concluded between Lebanon and Israel defining a maritime border between the two countries (thus enabling the economic exploitation of natural gas fields). In November the ISG noted with concern the lack of co-operation among Lebanese political actors who had failed to elect a new President to replace Aoun, whose term of office had ended on 31 October. The Special Coordinator convened a series of consultations with stakeholders, including youth and women’s representatives, political and religious figures, and economic experts who addressed the urgent domestic reforms required as a prerequisite to realizing a provisional staff agreement with the International Monetary Fund that had been reached in April.</p>
                    <p>
          In March 2023, reiterating statements made by the UN Secretary-General and the ISG, the Special Coordinator expressed grave concern over the failure thus far to elect a new Lebanese President and resolve the political vacuum that had prevailed since the end of October 2022. She emphasized that the delay was contributing to the paralysis of state institutions and to the extreme and ever deepening national socioeconomic crisis. From early 2023 UNSCOL oversaw a UNDP-managed financial transfer and accountability mechanism that had been established as a framework for a USA-financed programme that aimed to provide livelihood support to Lebanon’s underfunded security forces. During mid-2023 the Special Coordinator engaged in several rounds of meetings with Lebanese stakeholders, including members of parliament, the commander of the national armed forces, and religious leaders. In early November, in advance of a Joint Arab-Islamic Extraordinary Summit that was convened in that month by the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="LAS.IO">League of Arab States</xr>
           and 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="OIC.IO">Organization of Islamic Cooperation</xr>
           to discuss the devastating escalation since October of Hamas-Israel conflict, she met with several Arab ambassadors to address the need to shield Lebanon from repercussions of the developing crisis. During that month the Independent Oversight Board of the 3RF strongly urged the Lebanese authorities to adopt an adequate social protection system. In February 2024 the Special Coordinator reiterated the urgent need to de-escalate hostilities in the Blue Line border zone with Israel, which had intensified and expanded in geographical scope since October 2023. She continued in early 2024 to engage with potential donors to secure support for the Lebanese military. In March the UN Secretary-General—while welcoming ongoing efforts by Lebanon’s caretaker authorities to finalize a national emergency preparedness plan—urged that resolute steps be taken towards the election of a new Lebanese President.
        </p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-block>
     </int-org-entry>
     <int-org-entry id="IO-UN.PB.0004" iso="io-un.pb.0004" print-style="COLUMN" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-ENTRYREF" usage="ewyb edio mena">
