               <p-group>
                    <heading>Establishment and Mandate</heading>
                    <p>UNAMA was established by the UN Security Council in March 2002, in order to fulfil tasks assigned to the UN under the December 2001 Bonn Agreement on provisional arrangements for Afghanistan and to co-ordinate the activities of the UN system in Afghanistan. During 2006-10 UNAMA assisted the Afghan Government with the implementation of the successor Afghanistan Compact, a framework for co-operation between the Afghan authorities, the UN and the international community. During 2010-14 the mission supported the Government in implementing the Afghan-led Afghanistan National Development Strategy: Prioritization and Implementation Plan (`Kabul Process’), aimed at transferring civilian and military responsibilities to full Afghan ownership and leadership. During 2015-August 2021 UNAMA and the Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General (SRSG) focused on strengthening Afghan sovereignty, leadership and ownership in the framework of Afghanistan’s Transformation Decade (2015-24). In March 2022, reflecting the altered political landscape arising from the Taliban takeover of Afghanistan in August 2021, UNAMA was tasked by the UN Security Council with focusing on the co-ordination and facilitation of humanitarian support; the co-ordination of international donors and support agencies; the provision of good offices and outreach; the protection of human rights (the Office of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights hosts the mission’s Human Rights Unit); the promotion of responsible governance and rule of law; and enhancing regional co-operation. It maintains a number of field offices across Afghanistan. In March 2024 the mission’s mandate was extended until 17 March 2025. UNAMA, with the UN Office on Drugs and Crime, co-chairs a Working Group on Counter-Narcotics focused on Afghanistan.</p>
                    <p>UNAMA’s electronic Protection of Civilians database has systematically collected and analysed information on casualties of conflict. On-site investigations have also been conducted by the mission to verify reports of civilian casualties.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Activities</heading>
                    <p usage="edio sasia">From 2013 UNAMA provided secretariat support to an Afghan People’s Dialogue on Peace, and assisted with a series of focus group discussions across the country that were to form the basis of provincial roadmaps for peace. The mission supported the organization of provincial council elections and the first round of a presidential election that were held in April 2014, and the second round of the presidential election staged in June. UNAMA also worked to promote freedom of the media, and provided capacity building and technical assistance to the Independent Election Commission. The preliminary results of the June poll were disputed by one of the presidential candidates, who made allegations of fraud against the authorities. Following partly UN-facilitated negotiations to resolve the impasse, it was agreed that the Commission would—under UNAMA-co-ordinated international supervision—conduct an audit of the 8m. ballots cast. On 26 September the Independent Election Commission declared that Dr Mohammad Ashraf Ghani Ahmadzai had secured 55.27% of the vote in the presidential ballot.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sasia">In March 2015 the Security Council welcomed the commencement of Afghanistan’s Transformation Decade (2015-24), and called for UNAMA and the SRSG to continue their role in co-ordinating international civilian efforts, in accordance with the principle of strengthening Afghan sovereignty, leadership and ownership. In January 2016 the mission welcomed the inaugural meeting of a new Quadrilateral Coordination Group (QCG) on Afghanistan, comprising officials from Afghanistan, China, Pakistan and the USA. In mid-September, in an address to the UN Security Council, the SRSG emphasized the urgency of exploring avenues to peace in Afghanistan, and enabling the country to achieve self-reliance. In October 2017 UNAMA, the International Election Commission and the Electoral Complaints Commission adopted a Project Document providing the legal and financial framework for UN and donor support to legislative elections scheduled to be held in the following year (having been postponed from October 2016). The UN Security Council reported in July 2018 that the voter registration process had been completed (and that around one-third of the 8.8m. registered voters were female). The elections were held, as planned on 20 October. In spite of several attacks at polling stations UNAMA expressed satisfaction at voter turnout. In the following month it published a special report on electoral violence.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sasia">Both the incumbent President Dr Ghani and a rival candidate Dr Abdullah Abdullah claimed victory at the (postponed) Afghan presidential election that was held on 28 September 2019. Dr Ghani was controversially formally declared the winner in February 2020. UNAMA welcomed a reduction in violence in February during the course of negotiations between the Taliban leadership and US representatives. On 29 February a USA-Taliban accord was reached, and related declaration issued, incorporating a joint commitment to work towards a peace agreement to end the war in Afghanistan, to protect Afghans’ rights, to contribute to regional stability and to global security, and to pave the way for the initiation of intra-Afghan peace negotiations. Under the deal, US troops were to be reduced to 8,600 by July, and to be fully withdrawn from Afghanistan—ending a two-decade presence there—by mid-2021. The Taliban, in turn, committed to preventing international terrorist groupings from conducting activities from Afghan territory. Also in the context of the agreement and declaration, the Afghan authorities and the Taliban were to release prisoners, as a confidence-building measure. Dr Ghani signed a decree in March 2020 that provided for the release, in two phases, of 5,000 Taliban prisoners (who were obligated not to return to combat). On 11 May, however, the Afghan Government suspended prisoner releases (numbering 1,000 by that stage), claiming that the 276 prisoners hitherto released by the Taliban included civilians who had been abducted after the conclusion of the 29 February agreement. On 12 May the UN Secretary-General strongly condemned terrorist atrocities perpetrated against a Médecins Sans Frontières maternity ward at the Dasht-e-Barchi Hospital in Kabul, in which at least 24 civilians, including women and children, were killed, and against a funeral in Nangarhar. In response to the continuing violence, Dr Ghani announced that the national security forces would resume offensive operations against the Taliban. Days later the SRSG welcomed a power-sharing accord concluded by President Ghani and Dr Abdullah, under which Ghani was to remain as President, while Dr Abdullah was to lead the proposed peace negotiations with the Taliban, and both men were to appoint an equal number of government ministers. A videoconferenced Security Council meeting on Afghanistan held in late June urged the Afghan Government promptly to continue the process of releasing Taliban prisoners, as preparations to enable the initiation of the proposed intra-Afghan talks; eventually agreement on the release of Taliban detainees was reached.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sasia">In mid-September 2020 negotiations aimed at achieving a comprehensive and sustainable peace agreement were initiated, in Doha, Qatar, between the Afghan Government and Taliban leaders. The UN Secretary-General announced at that time that the UN would remain in close contact with both sides. An Afghanistan Partnership Framework (covering 2021-24) and Afghanistan National Peace and Development Plan were agreed at the 2020 Afghanistan Conference, convened under UN auspices, with participation by the SRSG, in a hybrid (part-virtual) format from Geneva, in November. In mid-March 2021, six weeks prior to the (then) scheduled withdrawal of US forces from Afghanistan, the Afghan Government and the Taliban, meeting in Moscow, Russian Federation, agreed to try to accelerate the pace of the peace negotiations, which had stalled over allegations by the Government that the Taliban was still instigating violence. At that time the so-called Troika Plus on Afghanistan—USA, the People’s Republic of China, Pakistan and Russia—called for an immediate ceasefire, and urged the Taliban not to launch new offensives, stating that economic and other assistance would be forthcoming once a peace settlement was in place.&#160;In mid-April the deadline for the full withdrawal from Afghanistan of US and allied NATO troops was extended to 11 September (the 20th anniversary of the major 2001 terrorist attacks against the USA). Meanwhile, UNAMA continued to engage with stakeholders at national, regional and international level and to implement local peace initiatives and confidence-building measures, with a particular focus on the inclusion of women and youth. The mission was also promoting measures to prevent the spread of COVID-19.</p>
                    <p>
          In early July 2021 representatives of UNAMA participated in a ministerial meeting that was organized by the UN and the Afghan and Turkmen Governments to address the stalled Afghan peace process (initiated in September 2020) and the impact of the ongoing withdrawal of international forces from Afghanistan. The Afghan National Army was proving unable to prevent a very rapid expansion of Taliban militant control over provincial centres and key strategic corridors. The Deputy SRSG urged support for Afghanistan through existing regional formats for co-operation such as the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="WB0231XD.IO.TXT.44">Shanghai Cooperation Organization</xr>
           and the Troika Plus on Afghanistan (China, Pakistan, Russia and the USA). At the end of July UNAMA strongly condemned an attack against its premises in Herat. In early August the UN Security Council reiterated its support for UNAMA, in the context of escalating conflict, and insisted that any deliberate targeting of civilians or UN personnel could constitute war crimes. On 13 August the UN Secretary-General outlined the dire humanitarian and security crisis that was developing in Afghanistan, reminded the Taliban and national security forces of their legal and moral duty to take all possible measures to protect civilians, and emphasized the carnage that was being caused by urban warfare. He called on the Taliban immediately to halt the offensive and to re-enter, in good faith, into the negotiations process towards an Afghan-led political settlement. On 15 August the Taliban, having swiftly captured almost all of Afghanistan’s other cities, took control of Kabul and stated the intent of declaring an Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan. The incumbent Afghan President, Dr Mohammad Ashraf Ghani Ahmadzai, fled the country. It was reported soon afterwards that UNAMA personnel had been relocated on a temporary basis to AlmatI, Kazakhstan. In mid-September the UN Security Council requested UNAMA to continue to co-ordinate humanitarian assistance to the Afghan people. From August onwards senior UNAMA and other UN representatives interacted regularly with the new Taliban authorities to advocate for the protection of fundamental rights and freedoms. Girls’ right to education and women’s right to participate fully in public and political life were particularly emphasized. The mission continued to engage with women’s organizations and other civil society stakeholders. In late September the Taliban suspended the national Constitution, pending a review of the compliance of existing laws with Shari`a.
        </p>
                    <p usage="edio sasia">In January 2022 the UN Secretary-General reported that, while the overall level of conflict had significantly decreased, Afghanistan was facing multiple crises, including the lack of an inclusive government, a massive economic contraction and a mounting humanitarian emergency. Although the Taliban authorities had announced amnesties for members of the former administration and security forces, UNAMA had received credible allegations of killings and of enforced disappearances. At that time the UN Secretary-General—emphasizing that Afghanistan was a diverse multi-ethnic society—recommended that the future overall UN political presence there should comprise two pillars: political/governance and humanitarian/development. Addressing an Economy of Afghanistan Conference that was convened by the Taliban in January, the SRSG emphasized that innovation—necessitating education for all (including for girls and women), technical capacity, creativity and diversity—underpins economic growth.</p>
                    <p>In March 2022 the UN Security Council adopted Resolution 2626, which provided for the continued formal presence in Afghanistan of UNAMA and other UN agencies. The mission was tasked with co-ordinating and facilitating the provision of essential humanitarian support to the population of Afghanistan; co-ordinating international donors and agencies that were working to supply the basic needs of the Afghan population; facilitating structured policy dialogue between stakeholders; extending good offices and outreach; promoting responsible governance and rule of law; monitoring the situation of civilians; advocating for the human rights of all Afghans (including the protection of women’s and girls’ rights); protecting children and reporting on abuses against them; supporting regional co-operation; and supporting existing mechanisms to improve the security situation in Afghanistan. Gender mainstreaming was designated a cross-cutting dimension of the mission’s mandate. Mine action to clear improvised explosive devices (IEDs) and other unexploded remnants of war was to be a priority of the UN presence. Later in March, the UN Secretary-General stated deep regret over a recently reported decision by the Taliban formally to suspend secondary education provision for girls. Shortly afterwards the UN Security Council also stated great concern at this development, and requested the SRSG to continue to advocate for girls’ right to education. In early May UNAMA stated deep concern at a recent Taliban directive that women should only leave their homes in circumstances where this was necessary, should cover their faces when appearing in public, and that violations of the directive would lead to the punishment of male relatives.</p>
                    <p>In mid-December 2022 the SRSG stated great concern at recent terrorist attacks (that caused significant civilian casualties) against the embassies of the Russian Federation (in September) and Pakistan (earlier in December), as well as against a hotel accommodating many Chinese nationals (also in December). In the same month UNAMA deplored a decree by the Taliban that banned women’s participation in higher education. The UN Secretary-General protested a Taliban edict that was publicized shortly afterwards that also withdrew women’s right to work for non-governmental and international organizations. In late April 2023 the UN Security Council unanimously adopted Resolution 2681, which condemned the Taliban’s recent decision to ban Afghan women from working for UN agencies in that country and expressed concern that it would severely impact the ability of UNAMA to implement its mandate.</p>
                    <p>In June 2023 the UN Secretary-General reported that the Taliban was continuing to consolidate its hold on power, and was—by means of repressive measures—maintaining national stability. Unprecedented levels of humanitarian need were reported across all 34 provinces of Afghanistan. A new UN Strategic Framework for Afghanistan, covering the period 2023-25, was launched in July by the SRSG, who reiterated the need for an enabling environment to be provided by the Taliban authorities to ensure its effectiveness in supporting the Afghan people to meet their basic needs. In August UNAMA released a report that addressed human rights abuses that had been perpetrated during the period 15 August 2021-30 June 2023 against former Afghan government and security officials—including 424 incidents of arbitrary arrests and detention, 144 of ill treatment and torture, 218 extrajudicial killings, and 14 enforced disappearances. The report found that only extremely limited efforts, lacking in transparency, had been made by the Taliban authorities to investigate these crimes. In November the Taliban issued a directive that prohibited women from participation in certain types of health care work.</p>
                    <p>In January 2024 the UN Secretary-General reported a recent decrease in attacks in Afghanistan by Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant-Khorasan, attributed to both a change in strategy and the impact of counter-terrorism efforts by the Taliban. In mid-February he organized, in Doha, Qatar, the second in a series of meetings of special envoys on Afghanistan, to address means of expanding structured international engagement. (The first had been held in May 2023.) At the end of that month he reported that the Taliban was continuing to curtail women’s rights in all spheres of public life—including through the arrest and detention of women deemed not to be in full compliance with the enforced the use of hijabs. Attacks targeting the Hazara Shi’a and other minority communities, as well as against former government and security force members, were reported to be ongoing: the Taliban was urged to hold the perpetrators to account. In early 2024 UNAMA was continuing to facilitate outreach meetings addressing governance-related issues, including with regard to human rights and to service delivery. The mission was liaising with the Taliban over the treatment of detainees.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sasia">By January 2024 a Special Trust Fund for Afghanistan (established in 2021) had mobilized US&#8201;$212.1m. to support the delivery of basic supplies to the country, through integrated initiatives, with a strong focus on promoting women’s participation. Also in January, the first disbursement from a Fund for the Afghan People was agreed: this aimed to resolve Afghanistan’s arrears with the Asian Development Bank.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-block>
     </int-org-entry>
