               <p-group>
                    <heading>Establishment and Mandate</heading>
                    <p>UNAMI was founded by Security Council Resolution 1500 (14 August 2003), expanded on 10 August 2007 by Resolution 1770, to support post-conflict Iraq. On 19 August 2003, just after the mission’s inception, terrorist attacks on the UNAMI headquarters in the Iraqi capital, Baghdad, killed the first Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General (SRSG) for Iraq, Sergio Vieira de Mello, and 21 other UN personnel. UN international staff were subsequently withdrawn from Iraq, until the formation of the Iraqi Interim Government at the end of June 2004.</p>
                    <p>Security Council Resolution 2631, adopted in May 2022, tasked the mission with supporting the advancement of inclusive political dialogue and reconciliation; efforts to strengthen electoral preparation and processes; security sector reform; regional dialogue and co-operation; co-ordination and delivery of humanitarian and medical assistance; dignified returns or local integration of refugees and displaced persons; the strengthening of essential services; efforts to advance human rights and judicial and legal reforms; gender mainstreaming; the strengthening of child protection; and structured dialogue between the Iraqi Government and the Kurdistan Regional Government. In May 2023 the UN Security Council extended the mission’s mandate until 31 May 2024, its core tasks unaltered. The SRSG was requested to prioritize the extension of assistance to the Iraqi authorities and people with regard to advancing inclusive political dialogue and national reconciliation. The SRSG and UNAMI were to assist the authorities in strengthening electoral processes, implementing constitutional provisions, developing processes for resolving disputed internal boundaries, and implementing security sector reforms. The UN Secretary-General was requested to provide to the Security Council an independent strategic review of UNAMI, in consultation with the Government of Iraq. In October 2023 the Secretary-General appointed Volker Perthes (a German diplomat and academic) as the Head of the Independent Strategic Review. UNAMI comprises an Office of Political Affairs and Analysis, an Office of Electoral Assistance, a Development Support Office, a Human Rights Office (HRO), a Public Information Office, and a Gender Unit.</p>
                    <p>In early 2007 UNAMI facilitated and observed the process of establishing Iraq’s Independent High Electoral Commission (IHEC), and subsequently the mission has supported the IHEC in capacity and institution building. UNAMI participates in meetings of the IHEC Board of Commissioners, and has served in an impartial advisory capacity in the process of selecting commissioners.</p>
                    <!--mandate to be revised to give priority to political good offices, facilitating humanitarian assistance, and supporting human rights and the rule of law ; carry out census-->
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Activities</heading>
                    <p>With regard to reconstruction and development, UNAMI aims to address the long-term challenge of achieving sustainable food security; to strengthen the overall quality of education and service delivery at all levels; to support policy development, and preserve and conserve the tangible and intangible Iraqi cultural heritage; to improve the human development situation in Iraq and promote good governance; to support the national health strategy of the Iraqi Ministry of Health in meeting basic health needs; to formulate and implement programmes on institutional/policy reform, capacity building, and service provision necessary to rehabilitate and develop the infrastructure of human settlements; and to support the Iraqi authorities in providing adequate assistance and effective protection to, and durable solutions for, uprooted populations in Iraq.</p>
                    <p usage="edio mena">In September 2017 the UN Secretary-General described as `destabilizing’ a referendum on possible independence organized unilaterally in that month by the Kurdistan Regional Government, including in areas—such as Kirkuk—that were not recognized by the Iraqi federal authorities as belonging to Kurdistan. In mid-November UNAMI urged the Kurdistan authorities to acknowledge a decision by the Iraq federal Supreme Court which confirmed that the September referendum in Kurdistan violated the provisions of the national Constitution and that therefore its results and effects should be annulled. In December UNAMI expressed deep concern over reports of violent unrest during demonstrations in the Sulaymaniyah area, urged restraint both by protesters and by the local authorities, and dispatched a fact-finding team. UNAMI subsequently undertook a series of meetings with Kurdistan youth that were aimed at fostering mutual understanding.</p>
                    <p usage="edio mena">UNAMI helped to organize a series of roundtable discussions in late 2017, with the aim of facilitating national reconciliation. In December the Iraqi authorities declared victory over Islamic State. In total, more than 4.5m. Iraqis had been liberated from the terrorist occupation. In mid-February 2018, at an International Conference for the Reconstruction of Iraq, convened in Kuwait, the UN Secretary-General launched an Iraq Recovery and Resilience Programme that had nine components, of which six were national in scope, and three were focused on building trust and economic opportunities in high-risk communities to prevent the emergence of violent extremism. UNAMI assisted the IHEC with the preparations for national and provincial elections that were held on 12 May—including by facilitating the participation of displaced persons in the elections, and with the utilization of new technology for managing election results.</p>
                    <p usage="edio mena">In early January 2020 the UN Secretary-General cautioned maximum restraint in response to the assassination on 2 January, on Iraqi soil, by a US air strike, of General Qassem Soleimani, commander of the elite Quds Force unit of the Iranian Revolutionary Guards Corps. The global coalition against Islamic State immediately suspended its combat operations in Iraq to focus on protecting its bases. On 6 January the Iraqi legislature passed a non-binding resolution demanding that foreign military forces withdraw from Iraq and cease using its land, waters and airspace.</p>
                    <p>The UN Secretary-General stated in February 2021 that the mission was continuing to report killings, other violence, abductions, disappearances and torture of participants arising from a wave of anti-Government protests that was initiated in central and southern areas of Iraq in October 2019 and was still ongoing. UNAMI extended enhanced technical support to the IHEC in advance of legislative elections that were held in October 2021 (postponed from June). In November the UN Secretary-General reported that the elections had been peaceful and well-managed. At that time the SRSG, participating in a conference that took place in Erbil to address gender equality and women’s empowerment strategies, welcomed the increased participation of women in the recent election, both as candidates and as voters. In March 2022 UNAMI issued a gender analysis of the October 2021 polls, which found that, of the 95 female candidates, 57 women (from 16 governorates) had won seats independently of the quota framework that had been in place. At the end of August—in response to an outbreak of violent protests in Iraq that had been prompted by the resignation of a key political actor, in the context of continued failure to achieve agreement on the composition of a new government—UNAMI urged a de-escalation of tensions, and respect for dialogue and for constitutional order. In October UNAMI welcomed the designation of a new government, under the premiership of Mohammed S. al-Sudani. In November 2023 UNAMI and the Iraqi Women Journalists Forum conducted a joint training event in Mosul (Nineveh). UNAMI engaged with relevant stakeholders, including the IHEC and a High Committee to Support Women’s Political Participation, in advance of Governorate Council elections that were held, in an orderly manner, in December. In January 2024 the UN Secretary-General reported that UNAMI was continuing to organize rounds of consultations with relevant parties to support the implementation of an agreement that had been concluded in October 2020 between the authorities in Baghdad and Erbil (Kurdistan) that was focused on establishing a new administrative structure in Sinjar (in Nineveh Governorate, northern Iraq).</p>
                    <p>The SRSG has repeatedly strongly condemned terrorist atrocities perpetrated in Iraq.</p>
                    <p>UNAMI’s HRO has prepared a series of reports addressing the human rights situation in Iraq, and has documented systematic and widespread severe violations of rights and of international humanitarian law perpetrated by Islamic State and affiliated armed groups, including murders, abductions and rape of civilians, looting, the trafficking and enslavement of women and children, the forced recruitment of children, and wanton destruction of places of religious or cultural significance.</p>
                    <p usage="edio mena">In March 2021 the UN Under-Secretary-General and SRSG on Sexual Violence in Conflict welcomed the recent adoption by the Iraqi Council of Representatives of a Yazidi Survivors’ Law, encompassing reparations, rehabilitation, and reintegration support (including through pensions, education, land, and public sector employment quota allocations) for members of the Yazidi, Christian, Shabak and Turkmen communities who had been subjected by Islamic State to crimes such as abductions and sexual violence.</p>
                    <p>In September 2017 the UN Security Council requested the Secretary-General to establish an independent investigative team, to be headed by a Special Adviser, to support Iraq’s efforts in holding Islamic State accountable for its actions. The ensuing UN Investigative Team to Promote Accountability for Crimes Committed by Da’esh/ISIL (UNITAD) was tasked with collecting and preserving evidence of acts committed by Islamic State that might amount to war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide. The Special Adviser was appointed in May 2018. In May 2021 the Head of UNITAD announced the completion of initial investigations into Islamic State attacks that had been perpetrated against the Yazidi community in Sinjar, and into the mass killing of unarmed military cadets and personnel at the Tikrit Air Academy in June 2014, and reported that `clear and convincing evidence’ had been established that genocide had been perpetrated against the Yazidis. In January 2023 the SRSG welcomed a decree by the Iraqi Council of Ministers that granted Yazidis ownership of residential lands and houses in Sinjar. In September 2023 the UN Security Council effected the fifth and final extension of UNITAD’s mandate (until 17 September 2024).</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-block>
     </int-org-entry>
     <int-org-entry id="IO-UN.PB.0018" iso="io-un.pb.0018" print-style="COLUMN" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-ENTRYREF" usage="ewyb edio ass">
          <int-org-entry-head>
               <int-org-name-group type="MAIN">
                    <org-entry-name>United Nations Assistance Mission in Somalia</org-entry-name>
                    <abbr>UNSOM</abbr>
               </int-org-name-group>
          </int-org-entry-head>
          <int-org-block>
               <address-block>
                    <address type="POSTAL">
                         <verbatim-address>Mogadishu, Somalia</verbatim-address>
                    </address>
                    <internet>unsom.unmissions.org</internet>
               </address-block>
               <dir-list>
                    <dir-entry sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="DIR-ENTRYREF">
                         <dir-entry-name>Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General and Head of Mission</dir-entry-name>
                         <person-group>
                              <person>
                                   <person-name>
                                        <forename>James</forename>
                                        <surname>Swan</surname>
                                   </person-name>
                                   <person-note>USA</person-note>
                                   <person-note>acting</person-note>
                              </person>
                         </person-group>
                    </dir-entry>
                    <!--deputy special rep i.2024 - Raisedon Zenenga of Zimbabwe-->
               </dir-list>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Establishment and Mandate</heading>
                    <p>The UN Assistance Mission in Somalia (UNSOM) was authorized by the UN Security Council in May 2013, under Resolution 2102, to supersede the former Political Office for Somalia (established in 1995). UNSOM was mandated to provide UN good offices functions in support of the peace and reconciliation process of the Federal Government of Somalia (inaugurated in August 2012); to monitor and help to prevent abuses of human rights and of humanitarian law; and to support the Federal Government and the African Union (AU) Mission in Somalia (AMISOM; on 31 March 2022 AMISOM was superseded by the AU Transition Mission in Somalia). UNSOM’s activities cover political affairs, integrated electoral support, support for rule of law and security institutions, preventing and countering violent extremism, human rights and protection, gender equality, women’s and youth empowerment, community recovery and extension of state authority and accountability, and environment (in particular furthering understanding of the nexus between climate issues and the root causes of violence in Somalia). UNSOM was requested by the Federal Government to deploy across Somalia, and by 2024 was maintaining offices in Mogadishu (the Somali capital), Baidoa, Beledweyne, Garoowe (Puntland), Hargeisa (Somaliland), Kismaayo. An agreement to establish an office in Dhusamareb (Galmudug) was concluded in February 2023; construction work was initiated in June.</p>
                    <p>The Mogadishu-based UN Support Office in Somalia (UNSOS), established in November 2015, extends critical logistics assistance to UNSOM, and generally in support of peacebuilding activities.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Activities</heading>
                    <p>The Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General (SRSG) undertakes mediation and good offices activities aimed at promoting reconciliation and dialogue, engaging with local leaders, the Federal Government, and with international partners. UNSOM has assisted the Federal Government with the development of a human rights roadmap, and has provided training for police and law enforcement officers, and human rights and humanitarian law guidance for personnel from the national armed forces. The mission has worked to eliminate the recruitment of children into the national military and into militias. The SRSG has repeatedly condemned atrocities by the terrorist organization al-Shabaab, and the serial targeting of members of the Somali Federal Parliament for assassination.</p>
                    <p usage="edio ass">In August 2020 the SRSG noted that the legal framework underpinning pending legislative and presidential elections had not been completed and that the necessary security arrangements were not yet in place. He urged broad-based co-operation among national stakeholders. On 17 September a model was broadly agreed, providing for an indirect voting format. (The SRSG subsequently urged that a one-person-one-vote universal suffrage model should be developed.) In December UNSOM police assumed responsibility for the co-ordination of election security training.</p>
                    <p>
          During 2021 UNSOM and UNDP jointly undertook to support the electoral process, through the extension of good offices and of technical, operational and logistical assistance. Owing to contention concerning the composition of the electoral management bodies and certain outstanding regional electoral issues, the planned legislative and presidential polls (which had been scheduled for February) were postponed, prompting violent unrest in Mogadishu. The UN Secretary-General stated grave concern over the violence, urging all parties to exercise restraint and calm. He called on the Federal Government and leaders of the Federal States urgently to reach consensus on a means of proceeding with the planned elections, on the basis of the so-called 17 September electoral model. He also urged respect for the right to peaceful assembly. Several rounds of Somali political consultations were subsequently held, seeking a resolution of the impasse. In mid-April UN and other international partners collectively stated deep concern over a recent decision by the Somali legislature to replace the `17 September’ agreement with a different electoral process that entailed a lengthy extension to the current presidential and parliamentary mandates. Later in the month they strongly condemned an eruption of violence in Mogadishu, reiterating that adherence to the 17 September arrangement should represent the only model for the electoral process, and that an extension of government mandates would cause a destabilizing political crisis. They stated particular concern over emerging fragmentation of the Somali National Army into clan-based factions. In late May they welcomed the decision made by a Federal Government of Somalia-Federal Member States summit, held on 27 May, to hold presidential and parliamentary elections promptly (within two months; this schedule was not, however, met), and thanked President Farmajo for having appealed at the beginning of the month for a reversion to the consensus-based 17 September electoral model. In mid-2021 the SRSG and representatives of AMISOM, the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IGAD.IO">Intergovernmental Authority on Development</xr>
           and the European Union (EU) visited Somalia’s federal member states with the aim of fostering constructive engagement in the electoral preparations. Legislative elections were initiated in November and were due to be completed on 15 March 2022; by that time, however, 40 of the 275 seats in the lower house remained unelected. The UN, AU, and other international partners issued a collective statement in mid-March that urged the prompt completion of the electoral process, and emphasized the need to adhere to a 30% quota of female parliamentarians. In late March the UN Security Council condemned a series of deadly terrorist attacks mounted by al-Shabaab with the stated intent of destabilizing the process. On 31 March the UN Security Council endorsed the new AU Transition Mission in Somalia (ATMIS), that replaced AMISOM. ATMIS was tasked with reducing the threat posed by al-Shabaab, assisting efforts to build the capacity of the Somali security and police forces, supporting national peacebuilding and reconciliation activities, and with undertaking a phased transfer of security responsibilities to Somalia. Senators and members of parliament were eventually inaugurated in mid-April (women having secured only 21% of the seats), and preparations for a presidential poll ensued. In early May 2022 the Security Council strongly condemned an al-Shabaab terrorist attack against an ATMIS operating base that caused the deaths of 10 Burundian troops. The SRSG welcomed the decisive election on 15 May of a new Somalian President, Hassan Sheikh Mohamud (marking the completion of the lengthy electoral process). Mohamud was inaugurated in early June. The SRSG subsequently continued to engage with regional leaders. He deplored continued sporadic terrorist atrocities (these included a lethal al-Shabaab attack in Mogadishu at the end of October that caused more than 100 fatalities).
        </p>
                    <p>The reported mobilization of armed groups, and persistent violence in Laascaanood (Somaliland), causing destruction of civilian infrastructure and widespread displacement, was condemned in early 2023; the UN and other international partners demanded an immediate de-escalation. In May landmark one-person-one-vote district council elections were organized in Puntland. In June the UN Secretary-General welcomed the Frontline States Initiative, including a Front Line States Task Force, which had been launched earlier in the year by Somalia and neighbouring states (Djibouti, Ethiopia and Kenya), with a view to advancing collective security activities aimed at countering al-Shabaab. In that context, the anti-al-Shabaab `Operation Black Lion’ was ongoing at that time. In June an UNSOM-UNDP joint programme on state-building and reconciliation was launched. The UN and other international partners urged the immediate de-escalation of tensions in Garowe in June, and, again, in Laascaanood, in August. In the latter month ATMIS and the Front Line States Task Force determined to strengthen collaboration. Concern was stated by the UN and other international partners in November over the mobilization of forces in Garowe. In January 2024 they welcomed the peaceful organization of a presidential election in Puntland. In that month the SRSG condemned a mortar attack that struck Aden Adde International Airport area, in Mogadishu, killing a UN guard. During the period 6 October 2023-24 January 2024 UNSOM reported 84 conflict-related civilian fatalities in Somalia. At the end of March 2024 the UN and other international partners commended national efforts to ensure Somalia’s compliance with international and regional human rights obligations, and acknowledged the intention of the authorities to finalize a national Constitution.</p>
                    <p>The UN, ATMIS, EU, Türkiye, UK and USA meet regularly, under Federal Government of Somalia auspices, as core security partners.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-block>
     </int-org-entry>
     <int-org-entry id="UN.IO.PB.BINUH.1" print-style="COLUMN" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-ENTRYREF" usage="ewyb edio sacac">
          <int-org-entry-head>
               <int-org-name-group type="MAIN">
                    <org-entry-name>United Nations Integrated Mission in Haiti</org-entry-name>
                    <abbr>BINUH</abbr>
               </int-org-name-group>
          </int-org-entry-head>
          <int-org-block>
               <address-block>
                    <address type="POSTAL">
                         <verbatim-address>Port-au-Prince, Haiti</verbatim-address>
                    </address>
               </address-block>
               <dir-list>
                    <dir-entry sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="DIR-ENTRYREF">
                         <dir-entry-name>Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General and Head of Office</dir-entry-name>
                         <person-group>
                              <person>
                                   <person-name>
                                        <forename>María Isabel</forename>
                                        <surname>Salvador</surname>
                                   </person-name>
                                   <person-note>Ecuador</person-note>
                              </person>
                         </person-group>
                    </dir-entry>
               </dir-list>
               <p-group id="PB.IO.BINUH.2">
                    <heading>Establishment and Mandate</heading>
                    <p>
          In June 2019 the UN Security Council authorized the establishment of the mission (the Bureau Intégré des Nations Unies en Haïti—BINUH), to follow on from an outgoing UN peacekeeping operation, with a mandate to contribute to multilateral efforts to consolidate peace and stability, as well as to further sustainable development in that country. BINUH became operational in mid-October. It was to advise the Haiti authorities on, 
          <i>inter alia,</i>
           strengthening the rule of law; developing a peaceful and stable environment, including through promoting human rights and supporting an inclusive inter-Haitian national dialogue; assisting governmental efforts to hold free, fair, and transparent elections; reinforcing the capacity of the Haitian National Police (HNP) in areas such as human rights, crowd control, maintaining public order, and gang violence response; developing an inclusive approach to reducing community violence; addressing human rights abuses; promoting compliance with international human rights obligations; improving prison standards; and strengthening the justice sector.
        </p>
                    <p>BINUH comprises an advisory political and good governance unit with a focus on promoting good governance, elections, constitutional reform, justice, and public sector accountability; a unit addressing gang violence, community violence reduction, and weapons and munitions management; a police and corrections unit (led by a UN Police Commissioner); a security unit; a human rights unit; and a mission support unit. BINUH was authorized to mainstream gender considerations in its work, as a cross-cutting issue.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sacac">In January 2020 BINUH and the Office of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights jointly issued a report that addressed an outbreak of extreme gang violence that had occurred in November 2019 in the deprived Bel Air neighbourhood of the Haitian capital, Port-au-Prince. The report concluded that Bel Air residents had not received adequate protection from the Haitian authorities.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sacac">Legislative elections that were initially to have been held in Haiti in October 2019 were postponed. From late 2019 opposition unrest escalated and demands intensified for the resignation of President Jovenel Moïse—whose rule was conducted by decree from January 2020, following the dissolution of the national legislature. In September 2020 President Moïse issued a decree that installed all nine members of the Provisional Electoral Council (the previous membership having resigned in July). Formal electoral assistance from the UN was requested in November. In January 2021 it was decreed that the first round of the postponed legislative elections would be rescheduled to September, to be held concurrently with a first round of a presidential election. Second rounds of the elections, and local and municipal polls, were to be held in November. A referendum on a new Constitution was to be organized in April (all subsequently postponed).</p>
                    <p usage="edio sacac">In February 2021 the Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General reported on recent significant opposition discontent, marked by protests, a failed attempted coup against President Jovenel Moïse on 7 February (on which date opposition activists had demanded that he should leave office), and the self-appointment as interim Head of State by a senior judge in that month. She outlined growing concerns over shrinking civic space, citing a decree on public security issued in November 2020 that had overly defined terrorist actions to encompass, for example, acts of vandalism, and an increase in threats targeted at lawyers, journalists, human rights defenders and members of the judiciary. She also stated deep concern over a recent resurgence of kidnappings, and persistent impunity for serious crimes. In late March large-scale demonstrations took place in Port-au-Prince and in other cities to protest the pending referendum on a new Constitution (which was to extend domestic political rights to the Haitian diaspora). Violence was reported in Bel Air in early April, resulting in three fatalities. On 7 July the UN Secretary-General condemned in the strongest terms the assassination of President Moïse, perpetrated by armed attackers at his residence in Pétion-Ville, Port-au-Prince. On 20 July Ariel Henry was inaugurated as acting President and acting Prime Minister. In August BINUH offered its full support to the Haitian authorities in the aftermath of a 7.2 magnitude earthquake, followed by flooding, that caused more than 2,200 fatalities and devastation in the Grand'Anse, Nippes and Sud areas of Haiti. Following the dismissal in September of a Moïse-appointed Provisional Electoral Council, national elections were postponed indefinitely.</p>
                    <p>
          In December 2021 the UN Secretary-General appointed an independent expert to lead a strategic assessment of BINUH’s mandate. The conclusions of the assessment, presented to UN Security Council members in April 2022, determined that BINUH should be empowered to continue its good offices and to scale-up support to the HNP to counter endemic gang violence. In February, the UN Secretary-General had strongly condemned an `alarming’ surge of criminal gang-related violence in Port-au-Prince, emphasizing the catastrophic effects of such disorder on the fundamental rights of Haitian citizens and on the Haitian economy. In October the Council unanimously approved targeted sanctions (including an arms embargo, asset freezes and a travel ban) against individuals participating in or facilitating gang violence. In that month BINUH and the Office of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights issued a report titled 
          <publ-name>Sexual violence in Port-au-Prince: a weapon used by gangs to instill fear</publ-name>
          , which stated that gang elements were using collective rapes (including of children and elderly people) as a tool of social control. At that time 60% of Port-au-Prince was reported to be dominated by armed gangs, whose sophisticated weapons were being trafficked into Haiti. An agreement on a National Consensus for an Inclusive Transition and Transparent Elections, signed in December by acting President and Prime Minister Ariel Henry and by opposition and civil society representatives, provided for a 14-month transition that included the establishment of transitional bodies and was intended to culminate in the inauguration of a newly elected government in February 2024. This schedule was not, however, adhered to.
        </p>
                    <p>In January 2023 the SRSG emphasized that political progress in Haiti would remain fragile without the deployment of an international specialized force to operate in conjunction with the HNP. A UN report issued in February found that, in a `nightmare’ environment beyond state control, mass incidents of murder, gang rape and indiscriminate lethal sniper attacks had escalated in the very impoverished community of Cité Soleil (near Port-au-Prince). In a joint report issued in May, BINUH and the Office of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights emphasized incidents of indiscriminate extreme violence, and an increase in vigilantism, including mob killings and lynchings of alleged gang members (164 murders were reported to have been perpetrated by vigilantes in April). A new SRSG, appointed in April, engaged local support for national dialogue and advocated for enhanced international assistance. BINUH and UNDP supported the organization during late May of a national political forum, in Port-au-Prince, with participation by a broad range of stakeholders. The forum issued a declaration that urged the deployment of `robust’ international operational support for the HNP, and the formulation of a national security policy. A further gathering of stakeholders was convened in the following month by CARICOM, in Kingston, Jamaica. In July the UN Secretary-General observed that the scope of a citizens’ vigilante movement, `Bwa Kale’, had extended from metropolitan Port-au-Prince to all 10 Haitian departments; a gang grouping, `Zam Pale’, was countering Bwa Kale. At the beginning of October, at Haiti’s request, the deployment was authorized by the UN Security Council of a new mission—the Multinational Security Support (MSS)—that was tasked with supporting the efforts of the HNP to quell the ongoing gang violence. The deployment of the MSS was, however, subsequently delayed. Eventually, on 1 March 2024, Kenya formally agreed to supply 1,000 officers to the mission. Shortly afterwards Haiti spiralled further into gang-led anarchy. On 11 March gang elements (which by then had control of around 80% of Port-au-Prince) forced the resignation of Ariel Henry. At that time a meeting of Haitian stakeholders and international development partners, convened under the auspices of CARICOM, agreed that a Transitional Presidential Council (comprising seven voting members and two observers) should be established and that the new Council should swiftly appoint an Interim Prime Minister; an inclusive Council of Ministers should then be established.</p>
                    <p>BINUH documented more than 8,400 direct victims of gang violence in 2023; 83% of gang-led atrocities occurred in Port-au-Prince, and the scope of such violence spread in that year into Artibonite (rural central Haiti). The mission has continued to facilitate inter-Haitian discussions among national stakeholders, addressing governance reforms, security, civic participation and elections, and to train and advise the HNP.</p>
                    <p usage="edio ewyb sacac">BINUH, UNDP, the HNP and other partners co-ordinate the Joint Programme for the HNP, a multi-donor basket fund on security in Haiti that was initiated in early 2022.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sacac">BINUH was also mandated to work on so-called legacy issues from previous UN peacekeeping missions. These included supporting efforts to eliminate cholera (an estimated 780,000 people in Haiti were infected with cholera during October 2010-October 2016, resulting in more than 9,000 fatalities), and addressing cases of sexual exploitation of civilians by UN troops.</p>
                    <p usage="edio ewyb sacac">BINUH supported efforts to address a severe outbreak of cholera that arose in Haiti in October 2022 and was ongoing in 2024.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-block>
     </int-org-entry>
     <int-org-entry id="IO-UNPOL.AUOFFICE.1" iso="io-unpol.auoffice.1" print-style="COLUMN" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-ENTRYREF" usage="ewyb edio ass">
          <int-org-entry-head>
