               <p-group>
                    <heading>Establishment and Mandate</heading>
                    <p>The Verification Mission, mandated to support the peace process in Colombia, was established in September 2017, in accordance with UN Security Council Resolution 2366, adopted in July. It succeeded the former UN Mission in Colombia, which was established in January 2016 by UN Security Council Resolution 2261, at the joint request of the Colombian Government and the rebel Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia—Ejército del Pueblo (FARC-EP). The Verification Mission was to act as the international component and co-ordinator of a tripartite (i.e. Government of Colombia/FARC-EP/UN) Monitoring and Verification Mechanism, with a primary focus on verifying the social, political and economic reintegration of former combatants; collective and personal security guarantees; and programmes on security and protection measures in conflict-affected areas. The mission was to maintain 10 regional offices and seven sub-offices, and a presence in 24 `former territorial areas for training and reintegration’, where former combatants were to be assisted to reintegrate into society. In October 2017 the Security Council expanded the mandate of the mission to include monitoring a temporary bilateral ceasefire between the Colombian Government and the rebel grouping Ejército de Liberación Nacional (ELN), which had entered into effect on 1 October. In May 2021 the Security Council expanded the mission’s mandate to include monitoring implementation of sentences to be issued by a Special Jurisdiction for Peace, which was established under the 2016 Final Agreement to investigate and prosecute those responsible for the most serious human rights violations committed during the civil conflict. In August 2023 the Security Council authorized the mission to monitor and verify implementation of a new ceasefire accord reached between the Government and the ELN. It also authorized the deployment of up to an additional 68 international observers. In October the UN Security Council extended the mission’s mandate until 31 October 2024.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Activities</heading>
                    <p usage="sacac edio">Establishing the preceding UN Mission in Colombia in late January 2016, the UN Security Council expressed its full commitment to the General Agreement to End the Conflict and Build a Stable and Lasting Peace that had been concluded in August 2012, in Havana, Cuba, by the Colombian authorities and FARC-EP. In February 2016 a multi-partner peacebuilding trust fund was established, which was to be managed jointly by the UN and the Colombian Government, and was to have a particular focus on supporting former conflict areas. In June, in Havana, the Colombian authorities and FARC-EP agreed to a formal cessation of hostilities and to the disarmament of FARC-EP. An advance team of mission observers was deployed in July, tasked with undertaking preparatory activities. A Final Agreement for Ending the Conflict and Building a Stable and Lasting Peace was concluded by the Colombian Government and FARC-EP, in Havana, in late August, and was formally signed, in Cartagena, Colombia, in September. At the end of September mission observers, nine representatives of the Colombian Government, and nine representatives of FARC-EP began to operationalize the Monitoring and Verification Mechanism. On 2 October, however, the provisions of the peace agreement were narrowly rejected by the electorate at a national referendum, and the Mechanism’s activities were temporarily suspended. None the less, the Government and FARC-EP reiterated their commitment to the ceasefire and cessation of hostilities, and the mission’s head supported and participated in a continuation of the negotiations process. In mid-October a new ceasefire protocol was concluded between parties to the conflict, and later in that month the UN Secretary-General requested the Security Council to authorize the mission to verify its implementation, pending the conclusion of a new final peace agreement. The tripartite Monitoring and Verification Mechanism officially resumed operations on 7 November. A few days later the Colombian and FARC-EP leaders announced the conclusion of a revised Final Agreement, and, following the signing of this later in that month, in Bogotá, and its subsequent ratification, it entered into force in December. A Commission for the Follow-up, Promotion and Verification of the Implementation of the Final Agreement, a National Reintegration Council, and a Colombian National Commission on Security Guarantees were to maintain a dialogue with the Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General (SRSG) and with the Monitoring and Verification Mission. During March-June 2017 mission observers undertook the process of verifying the disarmament of former militants at FARC-EP camps (this was formally completed on 27 June). By mid-August more than 8,100 weapons and more than 1.3m. incinerated cartridges had been removed from FARC-EP camps and arms caches and placed in storage. Unstable explosives found at the camps, such as grenades and anti-personnel mines, had been destroyed. FARC-EP formally transformed into a political party at the end of August.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sacac">In January 2018 the UN Secretary-General urged the Colombian Government and ELN to resume efforts to agree a stronger ceasefire, and tasked the SRSG with taking action to facilitate the resumption of bilateral negotiations between the two sides (which had been suspended in that month). The talks were resumed in March. On 31 July the SRSG met with representatives of both sides and endorsed their political declaration of a commitment to further dialogue, despite no agreements on social participation or on a ceasefire being reached at that time. In August, however, following the inauguration of the new Colombian President Iván Duque (elected in May-June) the Government halted the negotiations process with the ELN pending that grouping’s rejection of all criminal activities, including hostage taking and attacks against strategic oil pipelines. The ELN, in turn, indicated that it would only end such attacks if the Colombian military committed to a full bilateral ceasefire and ceased the pursuit of ELN combatants.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sacac">In July 2018 the UN Secretary-General reported that the mission, the Colombian authorities and FARC-EP had identified a series of measures aimed at advancing the implementation of the reintegration process for former combatants, and at enhancing security guarantees for the most conflict-affected local areas. He also noted a presidential decree issued in early May aimed at enabling access to land ownership for co-operatives of former combatants. In early July the mission celebrated the inaugural session of a new Congress, incorporating for the first time FARC-EP political representatives, further to legislative elections held in March. It was reported in September that, in contravention of the 2016 Final Agreement, several FARC-EP leaders had abandoned their territorial areas for training and reintegration in which they had been positioned. In late August 2019 the mission strongly condemned the decision by an FARC-EP faction to renounce the 2016 Agreement and to re-arm.</p>
                    <p usage="sacac">The UN Secretary-General reported in June 2020 that the implementation during that year of a mandatory COVID-19 lockdown and other containment measures had adversely affected some security guarantee mechanisms provided for under the Final Agreement, enabling illegal armed groupings and criminal entities to intensify their strategic presence and also to strengthen their control over strategic illicit trafficking routes.</p>
                    <p usage="edio sacac">In December 2021 the UN Secretary-General reported that violence by illegal armed actors in competition for territorial and social control was continuing, leading to large-scale killings and forced mass displacements. Many of the co-operating ex-combatants were reported to be at heightened risk of attacks, forced re-recruitment into militant groupings, and reprisals.Meeting in January and July 2022 the UN Security Council stated concern over continuing threats and assaults against and murders of former FARC-EP combatants who were participating in the peace process, as well as abuses and murders of community leaders. In June the Secretary-General acknowledged the democratic progress made by the country with the recent peaceful conduct of elections. He also welcomed the publication of the final report of the country’s Truth Commission. In late June a hearing was organized for the first case (`01’, involving seven former FARC-EP commanders) that was being addressed by the Special Jurisdiction for Peace, which had been established under the 2016 Final Agreement to ensure accountability for the most serious human rights violations committed during the civil conflict.</p>
                    <p>Upon taking office in August 2022, the new Colombian President Gustavo Petro pursued a policy aimed at achieving `Paz Total’ (Total Peace), which included a focus on dialogue with armed groups. In January 2023, at the request of the Colombian Government, the UN Security Council expanded UNVMC’s mandate to encompass monitoring the implementation of the chapters of the Final Peace Agreement that relate to comprehensive rural reform (progress had been made by the Petro administration in purchasing land and formalizing land tenure to provide stability for landless peasant farmers) and ethnic matters (with a focus on Indigenous and Afro-Colombians). A ceasefire between government forces and the dissident former FARC-EP faction Estado Mayor Central (EMC) was implemented from January; in May, however, the truce was suspended. In June, during a round of peace talks held in Cuba, the Colombian Government and the ELN concluded agreements that provided for a potentially renewable 180-day national bilateral ceasefire, to take effect on 3 August, and for the establishment of a mechanism to define social participation in the national peace process. On 2 August the Security Council expanded UNVMC’s mandate to monitor and verify the implementation of the ceasefire; subsequently 60 new observers and 46 new civilian staff were appointed to the mission. In February 2024 the ceasefire was extended for a further six-month period. In mid-October 2023 a renewed Government-EMC ceasefire entered into force; this was partially suspended in March 2024.</p>
                    <p>In late December 2023 the UN Secretary-General reported that, with regard to integration, nearly 80% of the more than 13,000 accredited former FARC-EP members were participating in 5,691 productive initiatives. By that time 406 targeted killings and 136 attempted murders of former FARC-EP combatants had been verified by the mission since the adoption of the Final Agreement. Furthermore, 35 former combatants were recorded as missing. Human rights defenders and social leaders were also under very significant threat; 13 killings of social leaders were verified during the period 27 September-26 December 2023.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-block>
